ng-v3", "object": "list", "usage": {"prompt_tokens": 1139, "total_tokens": 1139}, "id": "fc3c3a56-2a39-97a6-a861-7e826ce42bc4"}, "input": {"input": ["CATASTROPHIZING:Catastrophizing is a cognitive distortion where individuals expect the worst possible outcome in a situation", "CATATONIC SYNDROME:Catatonic syndrome is a side effect of Chlorpromazine, characterized by mutism, stupor, and rigidity", "CATECHOLAMINES:Catecholamines, including adrenaline and NE, can induce anxiety and trigger panic attacks in individuals with a history of such episodes", "CBT:Cognitive Behavioral Therapy, a psychological treatment used for phobias and other mental health conditions", "CCMD:The CCMD (Chinese Classification and Diagnostic Criteria of Mental Disorders) is a system developed by the Chinese Medical Association Psychiatric Branch to classify and diagnose mental disorders in China>", "CCMD-1:CCMD-1, the first edition of the Chinese Classification and Diagnostic Criteria of Mental Disorders, was established in 1986. It represents a significant milestone in the field of mental health in China, as it introduced a revised classification scheme and diagnostic standards specifically tailored to the three most common mental diseases. This foundational work laid the groundwork for subsequent editions and advancements in the diagnosis and classification of mental disorders in the Chinese context.", "CCMD-2:CCMD-2, the second edition of the Chinese Classification and Diagnostic Criteria of Mental Disorders, was officially approved in 1989. This comprehensive framework for the classification and diagnosis of mental disorders in China was developed following three years of extensive field testing and research to ensure its applicability and accuracy. Known in Chinese as 《中国精神疾病的分类方案和诊断标准》, CCMD-2 represents a significant milestone in the standardization of mental health diagnostics within the Chinese context.", "CCMD-2-R:The CCMD-2-R (Chinese Classification of Mental Disorders, 2nd Edition, Revised) is a diagnostic system used in China to classify mental health disorders. It was officially released in 1994 and serves as a key framework for mental health diagnosis within the country. The system retains traditional Chinese psychiatric terms, such as \"hysteria,\" while aligning its clinical descriptions with the internationally recognized ICD-10 (International Classification of Diseases, 10th Revision). Additionally, CCMD-2-R includes specific classifications for various mental disorders, such as dysthymic disorder, which it refers to as \"depressive neurosis.\" This integration of traditional terminology with modern diagnostic criteria reflects the system's effort to balance cultural specificity with global clinical standards. Overall, CCMD-2-R represents a significant tool in the Chinese mental health landscape, bridging historical practices and contemporary diagnostic approaches.", "CCMD-2R:CCMD-2R is the revised edition of the CCMD-2, approved in 1994 after revisions led by Professor Yao Chuanfang>", "CCMD-3:The **Chinese Classification of Mental Disorders, 3rd Edition (CCMD-3)** is a comprehensive diagnostic standard and classification system used in China for identifying, categorizing, and diagnosing a wide range of mental health disorders. Adopted by the Chinese Society of Psychiatry in 2001 and implemented nationwide, CCMD-3 serves as a critical tool for mental health professionals in China. It provides detailed criteria for diagnosing various conditions, including anxiety disorders (such as generalized anxiety disorder and panic disorder), obsessive-compulsive disorder (OCD) in both children and adults, post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD), and specific phobias. Additionally, CCMD-3 addresses neurotic disorders, such as neurotic bulimia, neurasthenia (characterized by brain and body function weakness, emotional symptoms, and physical fatigue), and hysteria, which has been moved out of the neurosis category in this edition.\n\nThe system also covers stress-related disorders, including acute stress disorder, and categorizes stress-related conditions under the broader umbrella of hysteria, stress, and neurosis. CCMD-3 includes diagnostic criteria for eating disorders like anorexia nervosa and binge eating disorder, as well as sleep disorders such as insomnia, hypersomnia, and sleep-wake rhythm disorders. It further classifies somatic symptom disorders, somatoform disorders, and tic disorders, including Tourette Syndrome.\n\nFor children and adolescents, CCMD-3 provides specific criteria for diagnosing developmental and behavioral disorders, such as ADHD, conduct disorder, and social anxiety disorder. It also addresses specific school skill disorders, including reading, writing, and calculation disorders, as well as speech and language impairments. The classification system retains the concept of neurasthenia and categorizes neurosis into various subtypes, while also addressing personality disorders and adaptation disorders.\n\nOverall, CCMD-3 is a robust and culturally adapted diagnostic manual that reflects the unique clinical and cultural context of mental health in China, offering a structured approach to the classification and diagnosis of mental disorders across all age groups."], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-v3"}}}